        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The good news is that this problem can be fixed by either Secretary of Transportation Pete Buttigieg using his rulemaking authority to expand the definition to cover all hazmat trains, or by Congress statutorily requiring the definition to reflect the National Transportation Safety Board’s original demands.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "But the bad news gets back to the shadowbanning: Because the story of Obama officials ignoring their safety regulators has been so thoroughly suppressed in favor of the “honorable Democrats, bad Republicans” tale, the problem — and the potential solution — are still getting too little attention.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
